<div id="bodyContent" class="vector-body" aria-labelledby="firstHeading" data-mw-ve-target-container>
<div class="vector-body-before-content">
<div class="mw-indicators">
<div id="mw-indicator-pp-default" class="mw-indicator"><div class="mw-parser-output"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Protection_policy#semi" title="This article is semi-protected due to vandalism"><img alt="Page semi-protected" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/1/1b/Semi-protection-shackle.svg/20px-Semi-protection-shackle.svg.png" decoding="async" width="20" height="20" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/1/1b/Semi-protection-shackle.svg/30px-Semi-protection-shackle.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/1/1b/Semi-protection-shackle.svg/40px-Semi-protection-shackle.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="512" data-file-height="512" /></a></span></div></div>
</div>

<div id="siteSub" class="noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>
</div>
<div id="contentSub"><div id="mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
<div id="mw-content-text" class="mw-body-content"><div class="mw-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang="en" dir="ltr"><div class="shortdescription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style="display:none">Total number of living humans on Earth</div>
<p class="mw-empty-elt">


</p>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:World_Population_Prospects.svg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/World_Population_Prospects.svg/220px-World_Population_Prospects.svg.png" decoding="async" width="220" height="165" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/World_Population_Prospects.svg/330px-World_Population_Prospects.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/World_Population_Prospects.svg/440px-World_Population_Prospects.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="900" data-file-height="676" /></a><figcaption>High, medium, and low projections of the future human world population<sup id="cite_ref-:4_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:4-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup></figcaption></figure>
<p>In <a href="/wiki/Demographics_of_the_world" title="Demographics of the world">world demographics</a>, the <b>world population</b> is the total number of humans currently living. It was estimated by the United Nations to have exceeded eight billion in mid-November 2022. It took around 300,000 years of human <a href="/wiki/Prehistory" title="Prehistory">prehistory</a> and <a href="/wiki/Human_history" title="Human history">history</a> for the human population to reach a billion and only 222 years more to reach 8&#160;billion.<sup id="cite_ref-:9_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:9-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The human population has experienced <a href="/wiki/Population_growth" title="Population growth">continuous growth</a> following the <a href="/wiki/Great_Famine_of_1315%E2%80%931317" title="Great Famine of 1315–1317">Great Famine of 1315–1317</a> and the end of the <a href="/wiki/Black_Death" title="Black Death">Black Death</a> in 1350, when it was nearly 370,000,000.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> The highest global <a href="/wiki/List_of_countries_by_population_growth_rate" title="List of countries by population growth rate">population growth rates</a>, with increases of over 1.8% per year, occurred between 1955 and 1975, peaking at 2.1% between 1965 and 1970.<sup id="cite_ref-:1_4-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:1-4">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> The growth rate declined to 1.1% between 2015 and 2020 and is projected to decline further in the 21st century.<sup id="cite_ref-:8_5-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:8-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> The global population is still increasing, but there is significant uncertainty about its long-term trajectory due to changing <a href="/wiki/Total_fertility_rate" title="Total fertility rate">fertility</a> and <a href="/wiki/Mortality_rate" title="Mortality rate">mortality</a> rates.<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/UN_Department_of_Economics_and_Social_Affairs" class="mw-redirect" title="UN Department of Economics and Social Affairs">UN Department of Economics and Social Affairs</a> projects between 9 and 10&#160;billion people by 2050 and gives an 80% <a href="/wiki/Confidence_interval" title="Confidence interval">confidence interval</a> of 10–12&#160;billion by the end of the 21st century,<sup id="cite_ref-:4_1-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:4-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> with a growth rate by then of zero. Other <a href="/wiki/Demography" title="Demography">demographers</a> predict that the human population will begin to decline in the second half of the 21st century.<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The total number of births globally is currently (2015–2020) 140 million/year, which is projected to peak during the period 2040–2045 at 141&#160;million/year and then decline slowly to 126&#160;million/year by 2100.<sup id="cite_ref-:2_8-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:2-8">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> The total number of deaths is currently 57&#160;million/year and is projected to grow steadily to 121&#160;million/year by 2100.<sup id="cite_ref-:3_9-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:3-9">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Median" title="Median">median</a> <a href="/wiki/Median_age" class="mw-redirect" title="Median age">age</a> of human beings as of 2020<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=World_population&amp;action=edit">&#91;update&#93;</a></sup> is 31 years.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_10-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-10">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<meta property="mw:PageProp/toc" />
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="History">History</span></h2>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Illustration_of_contemporary_and_past_human_populations_Our_World_in_Data.png" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d2/Illustration_of_contemporary_and_past_human_populations_Our_World_in_Data.png/220px-Illustration_of_contemporary_and_past_human_populations_Our_World_in_Data.png" decoding="async" width="220" height="328" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d2/Illustration_of_contemporary_and_past_human_populations_Our_World_in_Data.png/330px-Illustration_of_contemporary_and_past_human_populations_Our_World_in_Data.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d2/Illustration_of_contemporary_and_past_human_populations_Our_World_in_Data.png/440px-Illustration_of_contemporary_and_past_human_populations_Our_World_in_Data.png 2x" data-file-width="5201" data-file-height="7747" /></a><figcaption>Visual comparison of the world population in past and present</figcaption></figure>
<style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r1033289096">.mw-parser-output .hatnote{font-style:italic}.mw-parser-output div.hatnote{padding-left:1.6em;margin-bottom:0.5em}.mw-parser-output .hatnote i{font-style:normal}.mw-parser-output .hatnote+link+.hatnote{margin-top:-0.5em}</style><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Further information: <a href="/wiki/Estimates_of_historical_world_population" title="Estimates of historical world population">Estimates of historical world population</a> and <a href="/wiki/Human_history" title="Human history">Human history</a></div>
<p>Estimates of world population by their nature are an aspect of <a href="/wiki/Modernity" title="Modernity">modernity</a>, possible only since the <a href="/wiki/Age_of_Discovery" title="Age of Discovery">Age of Discovery</a>. Early estimates for the population of the world<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> date to the 17th century: <a href="/wiki/William_Petty" title="William Petty">William Petty</a>, in 1682, estimated the world population at 320 million (current estimates ranging close to twice this number); by the late 18th century, estimates ranged close to one billion (consistent with current estimates).<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> More refined estimates, broken down by continents, were published in the first half of the 19th century, at 600 million to 1&#160;billion in the early 1800s and 800&#160;million to 1&#160;billion in the 1840s.<sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>It is difficult for estimates to be better than rough approximations, as even current population estimates are fraught with uncertainties from 3% to 5%.<sup id="cite_ref-Kapitza2_14-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kapitza2-14">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Ancient_and_post-classical_history">Ancient and post-classical history</span></h3>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main articles: <a href="/wiki/Classical_demography" title="Classical demography">Classical demography</a> and <a href="/wiki/Medieval_demography" title="Medieval demography">Medieval demography</a></div>
<p>Estimates of the population of the world at the time agriculture emerged in around 10,000 BC have ranged between 1 million and 15&#160;million.<sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-16">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup> Even earlier, genetic evidence suggests humans may have gone through a population bottleneck of between 1,000 and 10,000 people about 70,000 BC, according to the now largely discredited <a href="/wiki/Toba_catastrophe_theory" title="Toba catastrophe theory">Toba catastrophe theory</a>. By contrast, it is estimated that around 50–60&#160;million people lived in the combined eastern and western <a href="/wiki/Roman_Empire" title="Roman Empire">Roman Empire</a> in the 4th century AD.<sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Plague_of_Justinian" title="Plague of Justinian">Plague of Justinian</a> caused Europe's population to drop by around 50% between the 6th and 8th centuries AD.<sup id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup> The population of Europe was more than 70 million in 1340.<sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19">&#91;19&#93;</a></sup> From 1340 to 1400, the world's population fell from an estimated 443 million to 350–375&#160;million,<sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-20">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup> with the <a href="/wiki/Indian_subcontinent" title="Indian subcontinent">Indian subcontinent</a> suffering the most tremendous loss and Europe suffering the <a href="/wiki/Black_Death" title="Black Death">Black Death</a> <a href="/wiki/Pandemic" title="Pandemic">pandemic</a>;<sup id="cite_ref-Essai_sur_l&#39;évolution_du_nombre_des_hommes_21-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Essai_sur_l&#39;évolution_du_nombre_des_hommes-21">&#91;21&#93;</a></sup> it took 200 years for European population figures to recover.<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">&#91;22&#93;</a></sup> The population of China decreased from 123 million in 1200 to 65&#160;million in 1393,<sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23">&#91;23&#93;</a></sup> presumably from a combination of <a href="/wiki/Mongol_Empire" title="Mongol Empire">Mongol</a> invasions, famine, and plague.<sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24">&#91;24&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Starting in AD 2, the <a href="/wiki/Han_dynasty" title="Han dynasty">Han dynasty</a> of <a href="/wiki/Ancient_China" class="mw-redirect" title="Ancient China">ancient China</a> kept consistent family registers to properly assess the poll taxes and labor service duties of each household.<sup id="cite_ref-nishijima_1986_pp595-96_25-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nishijima_1986_pp595-96-25">&#91;25&#93;</a></sup> In that year, the population of <a href="/wiki/Western_Han" class="mw-redirect" title="Western Han">Western Han</a> was recorded as 57,671,400 individuals in 12,366,470 households, decreasing to 47,566,772 individuals in 9,348,227 households by AD 146, towards the <a href="/wiki/End_of_the_Han_dynasty" title="End of the Han dynasty">end of the Han dynasty</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-nishijima_1986_pp595-96_25-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nishijima_1986_pp595-96-25">&#91;25&#93;</a></sup> From 200 to 400, the world population fell from an estimated 257 million to 206&#160;million, with China suffering the greatest loss.<sup id="cite_ref-Essai_sur_l&#39;évolution_du_nombre_des_hommes_21-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Essai_sur_l&#39;évolution_du_nombre_des_hommes-21">&#91;21&#93;</a></sup> At the founding of the <a href="/wiki/Ming_dynasty" title="Ming dynasty">Ming dynasty</a> in 1368, China's population was reported to be close to 60 million; toward the end of the dynasty in 1644, it may have approached 150&#160;million.<sup id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-26">&#91;26&#93;</a></sup> England's population reached an estimated 5.6&#160;million in 1650, up from an estimated 2.6&#160;million in 1500.<sup id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-27">&#91;27&#93;</a></sup> New crops that were brought to Asia and Europe from the Americas by Portuguese and Spanish colonists in the 16th century are believed to have contributed to population growth.<sup id="cite_ref-28" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-28">&#91;28&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-29" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-29">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-30">&#91;30&#93;</a></sup> Since their introduction to Africa by Portuguese traders in the 16th century,<sup id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31">&#91;31&#93;</a></sup> maize and <a href="/wiki/Cassava" title="Cassava">cassava</a> have similarly replaced traditional African crops as the most important <a href="/wiki/Staple_food" title="Staple food">staple food</a> crops grown on the continent.<sup id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32">&#91;32&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Pre-Columbian_era" title="Pre-Columbian era">pre-Columbian</a> population of the Americas is uncertain; historian David Henige called it "the most unanswerable question in the world."<sup id="cite_ref-33" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-33">&#91;33&#93;</a></sup> By the end of the 20th century, scholarly consensus favored an estimate of roughly 55 million people, but numbers from various sources have ranged from 10&#160;million to 100&#160;million.<sup id="cite_ref-34" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-34">&#91;34&#93;</a></sup> Encounters between European explorers and populations in the rest of the world often introduced local <a href="/wiki/List_of_epidemics" class="mw-redirect" title="List of epidemics">epidemics</a> of extraordinary virulence.<sup id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35">&#91;35&#93;</a></sup> According to the most extreme scholarly claims, as many as 90% of the <a href="/wiki/Population_history_of_indigenous_peoples_of_the_Americas" class="mw-redirect" title="Population history of indigenous peoples of the Americas">Native American population</a> of the <a href="/wiki/New_World" title="New World">New World</a> died of <a href="/wiki/Old_World" title="Old World">Old World</a> diseases such as <a href="/wiki/Smallpox" title="Smallpox">smallpox</a>, <a href="/wiki/Measles" title="Measles">measles</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Influenza" title="Influenza">influenza</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36">&#91;36&#93;</a></sup> Over the centuries, the Europeans had developed high degrees of immunity to these diseases, while the indigenous peoples had no such immunity.<sup id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-37">&#91;37&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Modern_history">Modern history</span></h3>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:2006megacities.svg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3d/2006megacities.svg/350px-2006megacities.svg.png" decoding="async" width="350" height="154" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3d/2006megacities.svg/525px-2006megacities.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3d/2006megacities.svg/700px-2006megacities.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="1425" data-file-height="625" /></a><figcaption>Map showing urban areas with at least one million inhabitants in 2006. Only 3% of the world's population lived in urban areas in 1800; this proportion had risen to 47% by 2000, and reached 50.5% by 2010.<sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38">&#91;38&#93;</a></sup> By 2050, the proportion may reach 70%.<sup id="cite_ref-39" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-39">&#91;39&#93;</a></sup></figcaption></figure>
<p>During the European <a href="/wiki/British_Agricultural_Revolution" title="British Agricultural Revolution">Agricultural</a> and <a href="/wiki/Industrial_Revolution" title="Industrial Revolution">Industrial Revolutions</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Life_expectancy" title="Life expectancy">life expectancy</a> of children increased dramatically.<sup id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-40">&#91;40&#93;</a></sup> The percentage of the children born in London who <a href="/wiki/Infant_mortality" title="Infant mortality">died before the age of five</a> decreased from 74.5% in 1730–1749 to 31.8% in 1810–1829.<sup id="cite_ref-Buer_41-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Buer-41">&#91;41&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-42" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-42">&#91;42&#93;</a></sup> Between 1700 and 1900, Europe's population increased from about 100 million to over 400&#160;million.<sup id="cite_ref-43" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-43">&#91;43&#93;</a></sup> Altogether, the areas populated by people of European descent comprised 36% of the world's population in 1900.<sup id="cite_ref-44" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-44">&#91;44&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Population growth in the Western world became more rapid after the introduction of <a href="/wiki/Vaccination" title="Vaccination">vaccination</a> and other improvements in medicine and <a href="/wiki/Sanitation" title="Sanitation">sanitation</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-45" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-45">&#91;45&#93;</a></sup> Improved material conditions led to the population of Britain increasing from 10 million to 40&#160;million in the 19th century.<sup id="cite_ref-46" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-46">&#91;46&#93;</a></sup> The population of the United Kingdom reached 60 million in 2006.<sup id="cite_ref-47" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-47">&#91;47&#93;</a></sup> The United States saw its population grow from around 5.3&#160;million in 1800 to 106 million in 1920, exceeding 307&#160;million in 2010.<sup id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-48">&#91;48&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The first half of the 20th century in <a href="/wiki/Russian_Empire" title="Russian Empire">Imperial Russia</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Soviet_Union" title="Soviet Union">Soviet Union</a> was marked by a succession of major wars, <a href="/wiki/Famine" title="Famine">famines</a> and other disasters which caused large-scale population losses (approximately 60 million excess deaths).<sup id="cite_ref-49" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-49">&#91;49&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-50" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-50">&#91;50&#93;</a></sup> After the collapse of the Soviet Union, Russia's population declined significantly – from 150 million in 1991 to 143&#160;million in 2012<sup id="cite_ref-51" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-51">&#91;51&#93;</a></sup> – but by 2013 this decline appeared to have halted.<sup id="cite_ref-52" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-52">&#91;52&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Many countries in the <a href="/wiki/Developing_world" class="mw-redirect" title="Developing world">developing world</a> have experienced extremely rapid population growth since the early 20th century, due to economic development and improvements in public health. China's population rose from approximately 430 million in 1850 to 580&#160;million in 1953,<sup id="cite_ref-53" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-53">&#91;53&#93;</a></sup> and now stands at over 1.3&#160;billion. The population of the <a href="/wiki/Indian_subcontinent" title="Indian subcontinent">Indian subcontinent</a>, which was about 125 million in 1750, increased to 389&#160;million in 1941;<sup id="cite_ref-54" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-54">&#91;54&#93;</a></sup> today, India, Pakistan and Bangladesh are collectively home to about 1.63 billion people.<sup id="cite_ref-55" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-55">&#91;55&#93;</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Java" title="Java">Java</a>, an island in <a href="/wiki/Indonesia" title="Indonesia">Indonesia</a>, had about 5 million inhabitants in 1815; it had a population of over 139&#160;million in 2020.<sup id="cite_ref-56" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-56">&#91;56&#93;</a></sup> In just one hundred years, the population of Brazil decupled (x10), from about 17 million in 1900, or about 1% of the world population in that year, to about 176&#160;million in 2000, or almost 3% of the global population in the very early 21st century. Mexico's population grew from 13.6&#160;million in 1900 to about 112&#160;million in 2010.<sup id="cite_ref-57" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-57">&#91;57&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-58" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-58">&#91;58&#93;</a></sup> Between the 1920s and 2000s, Kenya's population grew from 2.9&#160;million to 37 million.<sup id="cite_ref-59" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-59">&#91;59&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Milestones_by_the_billions">Milestones by the billions</span></h3>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/World_population_milestones" title="World population milestones">World population milestones</a></div>

</td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>The UN estimated that the world population reached one billion for the first time in 1804. It was another 123 years before it reached two billion in 1927, but it took only 33 years to reach three billion in 1960.<sup id="cite_ref-61" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-61">&#91;61&#93;</a></sup> Thereafter, it took 14 years for the global population to reach four billion in 1974, 13 years to reach five billion in 1987, 12 years to reach six billion in 1999 and, according to the United States Census Bureau, 13 years to reach seven billion in March 2012.<sup id="cite_ref-USCBcite_62-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-USCBcite-62">&#91;62&#93;</a></sup> The United Nations, however, estimated that the world population reached seven billion in October 2011.<sup id="cite_ref-UN7bn_63-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-UN7bn-63">&#91;63&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Guardian7_64-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Guardian7-64">&#91;64&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-UPI7bn_65-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-UPI7bn-65">&#91;65&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>According to the UN, the global population reached eight billion in November 2022,<sup id="cite_ref-auto_66-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-auto-66">&#91;66&#93;</a></sup> but because the growth rate is slowing, it will take another 15 years to reach around 9&#160;billion by 2037 and 20 years to reach 10&#160;billion by 2057.<sup id="cite_ref-:7_67-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:7-67">&#91;67&#93;</a></sup> Alternative scenarios for 2050 range from a low of 7.4&#160;billion to a high of more than 10.6&#160;billion.<sup id="cite_ref-WorldPopProspects_68-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WorldPopProspects-68">&#91;68&#93;</a></sup> Projected figures vary depending on underlying statistical assumptions and the variables used in projection calculations, especially the <a href="/wiki/Fertility" title="Fertility">fertility</a> and <a href="/wiki/Mortality_rate" title="Mortality rate">mortality</a> variables. Long-range predictions to 2150 range from a population decline to 3.2&#160;billion in the "low scenario", to "high scenarios" of 24.8&#160;billion.<sup id="cite_ref-WorldPopProspects_68-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WorldPopProspects-68">&#91;68&#93;</a></sup> One extreme scenario predicted a massive increase to 256&#160;billion by 2150, assuming the global fertility rate remained at its 1995 level of 3.04 children per woman; however, by 2010 the global fertility rate had declined to 2.52.<sup id="cite_ref-LongRangeProjections2003KeyFindings_69-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-LongRangeProjections2003KeyFindings-69">&#91;69&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Fertility2010_70-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fertility2010-70">&#91;70&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>There is no estimation for the exact day or month the world's population surpassed one or two billion. The points at which it reached three and four billion were not officially noted, but the International Database of the United States Census Bureau placed them in July 1959 and April 1974 respectively. The United Nations did determine, and commemorate, the "Day of 5 Billion" on 11 July 1987, and the "Day of 6 Billion" on 12 October 1999. The Population Division of the United Nations declared the "<a href="/wiki/Day_of_Seven_Billion" title="Day of Seven Billion">Day of Seven Billion</a>" to be 31 October 2011.<sup id="cite_ref-71" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-71">&#91;71&#93;</a></sup> The United Nations marked the birth of the <a href="/wiki/Vinice_Mabansag" class="mw-redirect" title="Vinice Mabansag">eight billionth person</a> on 15 November 2022.<sup id="cite_ref-72" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-72">&#91;72&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-auto_66-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-auto-66">&#91;66&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Global_demographics">Global demographics</span></h2>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Demographics_of_the_world" title="Demographics of the world">Demographics of the world</a></div>
<figure typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Expectancy_of_life.svg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fa/Expectancy_of_life.svg/400px-Expectancy_of_life.svg.png" decoding="async" width="400" height="174" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fa/Expectancy_of_life.svg/600px-Expectancy_of_life.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fa/Expectancy_of_life.svg/800px-Expectancy_of_life.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="2754" data-file-height="1200" /></a><figcaption><style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r1172904464">.mw-parser-output figure[typeof="mw:File/Thumb"] .image-key>ol{margin-left:1.3em;margin-top:0}.mw-parser-output figure[typeof="mw:File/Thumb"] .image-key>ul{margin-top:0}.mw-parser-output figure[typeof="mw:File/Thumb"] .image-key li{page-break-inside:avoid;break-inside:avoid-column}@media(min-width:300px){.mw-parser-output figure[typeof="mw:File/Thumb"] .image-key,.mw-parser-output figure[typeof="mw:File/Thumb"] .image-key-wide{column-count:2}.mw-parser-output figure[typeof="mw:File/Thumb"] .image-key-narrow{column-count:1}}@media(min-width:450px){.mw-parser-output figure[typeof="mw:File/Thumb"] .image-key-wide{column-count:3}}</style><style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r1126788409">.mw-parser-output .plainlist ol,.mw-parser-output .plainlist ul{line-height:inherit;list-style:none;margin:0;padding:0}.mw-parser-output .plainlist ol li,.mw-parser-output .plainlist ul li{margin-bottom:0}</style><div class="plainlist image-key"><ul><li><style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r981673959">.mw-parser-output .legend{page-break-inside:avoid;break-inside:avoid-column}.mw-parser-output .legend-color{display:inline-block;min-width:1.25em;height:1.25em;line-height:1.25;margin:1px 0;text-align:center;border:1px solid black;background-color:transparent;color:black}.mw-parser-output .legend-text{}</style><div class="legend"><span class="legend-color mw-no-invert" style="background-color:#0000CD; color:white;">&#160;</span>&#160;&gt;80</div></li><li><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959"><div class="legend"><span class="legend-color mw-no-invert" style="background-color:#4169E1; color:white;">&#160;</span>&#160;77.5–80</div></li><li><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959"><div class="legend"><span class="legend-color mw-no-invert" style="background-color:#00BFFF; color:black;">&#160;</span>&#160;75–77.5</div></li><li><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959"><div class="legend"><span class="legend-color mw-no-invert" style="background-color:#3CB371; color:black;">&#160;</span>&#160;72.5–75</div></li><li><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959"><div class="legend"><span class="legend-color mw-no-invert" style="background-color:#32CD32; color:black;">&#160;</span>&#160;70–72.5</div></li><li><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959"><div class="legend"><span class="legend-color mw-no-invert" style="background-color:#ADFF2F; color:black;">&#160;</span>&#160;67.5–70</div></li><li><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959"><div class="legend"><span class="legend-color mw-no-invert" style="background-color:#FFFF00; color:black;">&#160;</span>&#160;65–67.5</div></li><li><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959"><div class="legend"><span class="legend-color mw-no-invert" style="background-color:#FFD700; color:black;">&#160;</span>&#160;60–65</div></li><li><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959"><div class="legend"><span class="legend-color mw-no-invert" style="background-color:#FF8C00; color:black;">&#160;</span>&#160;55–60</div></li><li><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r981673959"><div class="legend"><span class="legend-color mw-no-invert" style="background-color:#FF4500; color:black;">&#160;</span>&#160;50–55</div></li></ul></div> 2015 map showing average life expectancy by country in years. In 2015, the World Health Organization estimated the average global life expectancy as 71.4 years.<sup id="cite_ref-WHOStats2016_73-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WHOStats2016-73">&#91;73&#93;</a></sup></figcaption></figure>
<p>As of 2020, the global <a href="/wiki/Human_sex_ratio" title="Human sex ratio">sex ratio</a> is approximately 1.01 males to 1 female.<sup id="cite_ref-cia-factbook_74-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cia-factbook-74">&#91;74&#93;</a></sup> Approximately 24.7% of the global population is aged under 15, while 65.2% is aged 15–64 and 10.1% is aged 65 or over.<sup id="cite_ref-cia-factbook_74-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cia-factbook-74">&#91;74&#93;</a></sup> The median age of the world's population is estimated to be 31 years in 2020,<sup id="cite_ref-:0_10-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-10">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> and is expected to rise to 37.9 years by 2050.<sup id="cite_ref-75" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-75">&#91;75&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>According to the <a href="/wiki/World_Health_Organization" title="World Health Organization">World Health Organization</a>, the global average <a href="/wiki/List_of_countries_by_life_expectancy" title="List of countries by life expectancy">life expectancy</a> is 73.3 years as of 2020, with women living an average of 75.9 years and men approximately 70.8 years.<sup id="cite_ref-76" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-76">&#91;76&#93;</a></sup> In 2010, the global <a href="/wiki/Fertility_rate" class="mw-redirect" title="Fertility rate">fertility rate</a> was estimated at 2.44 children per woman.<sup id="cite_ref-77" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-77">&#91;77&#93;</a></sup> In June 2012, British researchers calculated the total weight of Earth's human population as approximately 287&#160;million tonnes (630&#160;billion pounds), with the average person weighing around 62 kilograms (137&#160;lb).<sup id="cite_ref-78" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-78">&#91;78&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/International_Monetary_Fund" title="International Monetary Fund">IMF</a> estimated nominal 2021 <a href="/wiki/Gross_world_product" title="Gross world product">gross world product</a> at US$94.94&#160;trillion, giving an annual global per capita figure of around US$12,290.<sup id="cite_ref-79" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-79">&#91;79&#93;</a></sup> Around 9.3% of the world population live in <a href="/wiki/Extreme_poverty" title="Extreme poverty">extreme poverty</a>, subsisting on less than US$1.9 per day;<sup id="cite_ref-80" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-80">&#91;80&#93;</a></sup> around 8.9% are <a href="/wiki/Malnutrition" title="Malnutrition">malnourished</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-81" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-81">&#91;81&#93;</a></sup> 87% of the world's over-15s are considered <a href="/wiki/Literacy_rate" class="mw-redirect" title="Literacy rate">literate</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-82" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-82">&#91;82&#93;</a></sup> As of January 2024, there were about 5&#160;billion global Internet users, constituting 66% of the world population.<sup id="cite_ref-83" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-83">&#91;83&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Han_Chinese" title="Han Chinese">Han Chinese</a> are the world's largest single ethnic group, constituting over 19% of the global population in 2011.<sup id="cite_ref-84" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-84">&#91;84&#93;</a></sup> The world's most-spoken languages<sup id="cite_ref-85" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-85">&#91;a&#93;</a></sup> are English (1.132B), <a href="/wiki/Mandarin_Chinese" title="Mandarin Chinese">Mandarin Chinese</a> (1.117B), <a href="/wiki/Hindi" title="Hindi">Hindi</a> (615M), Spanish (534M) and French (280M). More than three billion people speak an Indo-European language, which is the largest language family by number of speakers. Standard Arabic is a language with no native speakers, but the total number of speakers is estimated at 274 million people.<sup id="cite_ref-86" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-86">&#91;85&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The largest religious categories in the world as of 2020 are estimated as follows: Christianity (31%), <a href="/wiki/Islam" title="Islam">Islam</a> (25%), <a href="/wiki/Irreligion" title="Irreligion">Unaffiliated</a> (16%) and <a href="/wiki/Hinduism" title="Hinduism">Hinduism</a> (15%).<sup id="cite_ref-Pew_87-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Pew-87">&#91;86&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Population_by_region">Population by region</span></h2>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Further information: <a href="/wiki/Demographics_of_the_world" title="Demographics of the world">Demographics of the world</a></div>
<p>Six of the Earth's seven <a href="/wiki/Continent" title="Continent">continents</a> are permanently inhabited on a large scale. Asia is the most populous continent, with its 4.64&#160;billion inhabitants accounting for 60% of the world population. The world's two most populated countries, India and China, together constitute about 36% of the world's population.
Africa is the second most populated continent, with around 1.34&#160;billion people, or 17% of the world's population.
Europe's 747 million people make up 10% of the world's population as of 2020,
while the <a href="/wiki/Latin_American" class="mw-redirect" title="Latin American">Latin American</a> and <a href="/wiki/Caribbean" title="Caribbean">Caribbean</a> regions are home to around 653 million (8%). Northern America, primarily consisting of the United States and Canada, has a population of around 368&#160;million (5%),
and Oceania, the least populated region, has about 42&#160;million inhabitants (0.5%).<sup id="cite_ref-88" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-88">&#91;87&#93;</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Antarctica" title="Antarctica">Antarctica</a> only has a very small, fluctuating population of about 1200 people based mainly in polar <a href="/wiki/Research_stations_in_Antarctica" title="Research stations in Antarctica">science stations</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-AntarcticCIA_89-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-AntarcticCIA-89">&#91;88&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<figure typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Population_pyramid_of_the_world_in_continental_groupings_2023.svg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fa/Population_pyramid_of_the_world_in_continental_groupings_2023.svg/300px-Population_pyramid_of_the_world_in_continental_groupings_2023.svg.png" decoding="async" width="300" height="237" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fa/Population_pyramid_of_the_world_in_continental_groupings_2023.svg/450px-Population_pyramid_of_the_world_in_continental_groupings_2023.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fa/Population_pyramid_of_the_world_in_continental_groupings_2023.svg/600px-Population_pyramid_of_the_world_in_continental_groupings_2023.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="2539" data-file-height="2003" /></a><figcaption><a href="/wiki/Population_pyramid" title="Population pyramid">Population pyramid</a> of the world in continental groupings in 2023. <p>Approximately 4.6&#160;billion people live in these ten countries, representing around 57% of the world's population as of July 2023.
</p><p>The UN estimates that by 2023 India will have overtaken China in having the largest population.<sup id="cite_ref-102" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-102">&#91;99&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-20230414france24_94-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-20230414france24-94">&#91;91&#93;</a></sup>
</p>

<div style="clear:both;" class=""></div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Most_densely_populated_countries">Most densely populated countries</span></h3>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Further information: <a href="/wiki/List_of_countries_and_dependencies_by_population_density" title="List of countries and dependencies by population density">List of countries and dependencies by population density</a></div>
<p>The tables below list the world's most densely populated countries, both in absolute terms and in comparison to their total populations, as of November 2022. All areas and populations are from <i><a href="/wiki/The_World_Factbook" title="The World Factbook">The World Factbook</a></i>, unless otherwise noted.
</p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Fluctuation">Fluctuation</span></h2>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main articles: <a href="/wiki/Population_growth" title="Population growth">Population growth</a>, <a href="/wiki/Projections_of_population_growth" title="Projections of population growth">Projections of population growth</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Population_dynamics" title="Population dynamics">Population dynamics</a></div>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:World_population_(UN).svg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/11/World_population_%28UN%29.svg/300px-World_population_%28UN%29.svg.png" decoding="async" width="300" height="266" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/11/World_population_%28UN%29.svg/450px-World_population_%28UN%29.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/11/World_population_%28UN%29.svg/600px-World_population_%28UN%29.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="1150" data-file-height="1020" /></a><figcaption>Estimates of population evolution in different <a href="/wiki/Continent" title="Continent">continents</a> between 1950 and 2050, according to the United Nations. The vertical axis is <a href="/wiki/Logarithmic_scale" title="Logarithmic scale">logarithmic</a> and is in millions of people.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Population size fluctuates at differing rates in differing regions. Nonetheless, population growth has been the long-standing trend on all inhabited continents, as well as in most individual states. During the 20th century, the global population saw its greatest increase in known history, rising from about 1.6&#160;billion in 1900 to over 6&#160;billion in 2000<sup id="cite_ref-111" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-111">&#91;104&#93;</a></sup> as the whole world entered the early phases of what has come to be called the "<a href="/wiki/Demographic_transition" title="Demographic transition">demographic transition</a>". Some of the key factors contributing to this increase included the lessening of the <a href="/wiki/Mortality_rate" title="Mortality rate">mortality rate</a> in many countries by improved sanitation and <a href="/wiki/History_of_medicine#Modern_medicine" title="History of medicine">medical advances</a>, and a massive increase in agricultural productivity attributed to the <a href="/wiki/Green_Revolution" title="Green Revolution">Green Revolution</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-112" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-112">&#91;105&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-113" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-113">&#91;106&#93;</a></sup> By 2000, there were approximately <a href="#Past_population">ten times as many people</a> on Earth as there had been in 1700.
</p><p>However, this rapid growth did not last. During the period 2000–2005, the United Nations estimates that the world's population was growing at an annual rate of 1.3% (equivalent to around 80 million people), down from a peak of 2.1% during the period 1965–1970.<sup id="cite_ref-:8_5-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:8-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> Globally, although the population <a href="/wiki/Population_growth" title="Population growth">growth rate</a> has been steadily declining from its peak in 1968,<sup id="cite_ref-114" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-114">&#91;107&#93;</a></sup> growth <a href="/wiki/Projections_of_population_growth#Growth_regions" title="Projections of population growth">still remains high</a> in <a href="/wiki/Sub-Saharan_Africa" title="Sub-Saharan Africa">Sub-Saharan Africa</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-115" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-115">&#91;108&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Total_Fertility_Rate_Map_by_Country.svg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/Total_Fertility_Rate_Map_by_Country.svg/300px-Total_Fertility_Rate_Map_by_Country.svg.png" decoding="async" width="300" height="154" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/Total_Fertility_Rate_Map_by_Country.svg/450px-Total_Fertility_Rate_Map_by_Country.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/Total_Fertility_Rate_Map_by_Country.svg/600px-Total_Fertility_Rate_Map_by_Country.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="1104" data-file-height="566" /></a><figcaption>Map of countries by fertility rate (2020), according to the <a href="/wiki/Population_Reference_Bureau" title="Population Reference Bureau">Population Reference Bureau</a></figcaption></figure>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:World_population_counter,_Eureka,_Halifax,_West_Yorkshire_(27th_August_2022)_001.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/World_population_counter%2C_Eureka%2C_Halifax%2C_West_Yorkshire_%2827th_August_2022%29_001.jpg/220px-World_population_counter%2C_Eureka%2C_Halifax%2C_West_Yorkshire_%2827th_August_2022%29_001.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="165" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/World_population_counter%2C_Eureka%2C_Halifax%2C_West_Yorkshire_%2827th_August_2022%29_001.jpg/330px-World_population_counter%2C_Eureka%2C_Halifax%2C_West_Yorkshire_%2827th_August_2022%29_001.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/World_population_counter%2C_Eureka%2C_Halifax%2C_West_Yorkshire_%2827th_August_2022%29_001.jpg/440px-World_population_counter%2C_Eureka%2C_Halifax%2C_West_Yorkshire_%2827th_August_2022%29_001.jpg 2x" data-file-width="5152" data-file-height="3864" /></a><figcaption>A world population clock in August 2022 at <a href="/wiki/Eureka!_(museum)" title="Eureka! (museum)">Eureka!</a> in <a href="/wiki/Halifax,_West_Yorkshire" title="Halifax, West Yorkshire">Halifax</a>, West Yorkshire</figcaption></figure>
<p>In fact, during the 2010s, Japan and some countries in Europe began to <a href="/wiki/Population_decline" title="Population decline">reduce in population</a>, due to <a href="/wiki/Sub-replacement_fertility" title="Sub-replacement fertility">sub-replacement fertility</a> rates.<sup id="cite_ref-BigDecline_110-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-BigDecline-110">&#91;103&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In 2019, the United Nations reported that the rate of population growth continues to decline due to the ongoing global demographic transition. If this trend continues, the rate of growth may diminish to zero by 2100, concurrent with a world population plateau of 10.9&#160;billion.<sup id="cite_ref-:8_5-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:8-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-:7_67-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:7-67">&#91;67&#93;</a></sup> However, this is only one of many estimates published by the UN; in 2009, UN population projections for 2050 ranged between around 8&#160;billion and 10.5&#160;billion.<sup id="cite_ref-116" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-116">&#91;109&#93;</a></sup> An alternative scenario is given by the statistician Jorgen Randers, who argues that traditional projections insufficiently take into account the downward impact of global urbanization on fertility. Randers' "most likely scenario" reveals a peak in the world population in the early 2040s at about 8.1&#160;billion people, followed by decline.<sup id="cite_ref-117" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-117">&#91;110&#93;</a></sup> Adrian Raftery, a <a href="/wiki/University_of_Washington" title="University of Washington">University of Washington</a> professor of statistics and of sociology, states that "there's a 70 percent probability the world population will not stabilize this century. Population, which had sort of fallen off the world's agenda, remains a very important issue."<sup id="cite_ref-118" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-118">&#91;111&#93;</a></sup>
</p>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Past_population">Past population</span></h3>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Estimates_of_historical_world_population" title="Estimates of historical world population">Estimates of historical world population</a></div>

<p>Using the above figures, the change in population from 2010 to 2015 was:
</p>
<ul><li>World: +420 million</li>
<li>Africa: +142 million</li>
<li>Asia: +223 million</li>
<li>Europe: +3 million</li>
<li>Latin America and Caribbean: +35 million</li>
<li>Northern America: +14 million</li>
<li>Oceania: +2.9 million</li></ul>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Projections">Projections</span></h3>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main articles: <a href="/wiki/Projections_of_population_growth" title="Projections of population growth">Projections of population growth</a> and <a href="/wiki/Future_generations" title="Future generations">Future generations</a></div>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1097763485"><table class="box-More_citations_needed_section plainlinks metadata ambox ambox-content ambox-Refimprove" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td class="mbox-image"><div class="mbox-image-div"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Question_book-new.svg" class="mw-file-description"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png" decoding="async" width="50" height="39" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/75px-Question_book-new.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/100px-Question_book-new.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="512" data-file-height="399" /></a></span></div></td><td class="mbox-text"><div class="mbox-text-span">This section <b>needs additional citations for <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability" title="Wikipedia:Verifiability">verification</a></b>.<span class="hide-when-compact"> Please help <a href="/wiki/Special:EditPage/World_population" title="Special:EditPage/World population">improve this article</a> by <a href="/wiki/Help:Referencing_for_beginners" title="Help:Referencing for beginners">adding citations to reliable sources</a>&#32;in this section. Unsourced material may be challenged and removed.</span> <span class="date-container"><i>(<span class="date">April 2020</span>)</i></span><span class="hide-when-compact"><i> (<small><a href="/wiki/Help:Maintenance_template_removal" title="Help:Maintenance template removal">Learn how and when to remove this message</a></small>)</i></span></div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>Long-term global population growth is difficult to predict. The United Nations and the US Census Bureau both give different estimates – according to the UN, the world population reached seven billion in late 2011,<sup id="cite_ref-UN_120-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-UN-120">&#91;113&#93;</a></sup> while the USCB asserted that this occurred in March 2012.<sup id="cite_ref-132" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-132">&#91;123&#93;</a></sup> Since 1951 the UN has issued multiple projections of future world population, based on different assumptions. From 2000 to 2005, the UN consistently revised these projections downward, until the 2006 revision, issued on 14 March 2007, revised the 2050 mid-range estimate upwards by 273&#160;million.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (May 2022)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>
</p><p>Complicating the UN's and others' attempts to project future populations is the fact that average global <a href="/wiki/Birth_rate" title="Birth rate">birth rates</a>, as well as <a href="/wiki/Mortality_rate" title="Mortality rate">mortality rates</a>, are declining rapidly, as the nations of the world progress through the stages of the demographic transition, but both vary greatly between developed countries (where birth rates and mortality rates are often low) and developing countries (where birth and mortality rates typically remain high). Different ethnicities also display varying birth rates.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (May 2022)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup> Both of these can change rapidly due to <a href="/wiki/Infectious_disease#Mortality_from_infectious_diseases" class="mw-redirect" title="Infectious disease">disease epidemics</a>, <a href="/wiki/List_of_wars" class="mw-redirect" title="List of wars">wars</a> and other mass catastrophes, or <a href="/wiki/Life_extension" title="Life extension">advances in medicine</a> and <a href="/wiki/Public_health" title="Public health">public health</a>.
</p><p>The UN's first report in 1951 showed that during the period 1950–55 the <a href="/wiki/Birth_rate" title="Birth rate">crude birth rate</a> was 36.9/1,000 population and the <a href="/wiki/Mortality_rate" title="Mortality rate">crude death rate</a> was 19.1/1,000.&#160; By the period 2015–20 both numbers had dropped significantly to 18.5/1,000 for the crude birth rate and 7.5/1,000 for the crude death rate.&#160; UN projections for 2100 show a further decline in the crude birth rate to 11.6/1,000 and an increase in the crude death rate to 11.2/1,000.<sup id="cite_ref-133" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-133">&#91;124&#93;</a></sup><sup>,</sup><sup id="cite_ref-134" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-134">&#91;125&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The total number of births globally is currently (2015–20) 140 million/year, is projected to peak during the period 2040–45 at 141&#160;million/year and thereafter decline slowly to 126&#160;million/year by 2100.<sup id="cite_ref-:2_8-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:2-8">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> The total number of deaths is currently 57 million/year and is projected to grow steadily to 121&#160;million/year by 2100.<sup id="cite_ref-:3_9-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:3-9">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>2012 United Nations projections show a continued increase in population in the near future with a steady decline in population growth rate; the global population is expected to reach between 8.3&#160;and 10.9&#160;billion by 2050.<sup id="cite_ref-135" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-135">&#91;126&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-136" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-136">&#91;127&#93;</a></sup> 2003 <a href="/wiki/United_Nations_Population_Division" class="mw-redirect" title="United Nations Population Division">UN Population Division</a> population projections for the year 2150 range between 3.2 and 24.8&#160;billion.<sup id="cite_ref-LongRangeProjections2003KeyFindings_69-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-LongRangeProjections2003KeyFindings-69">&#91;69&#93;</a></sup> One of many independent mathematical models supports the lower estimate,<sup id="cite_ref-137" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-137">&#91;128&#93;</a></sup> while a 2014 estimate forecasts between 9.3 and 12.6&#160;billion in 2100, and continued growth thereafter.<sup id="cite_ref-138" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-138">&#91;129&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-139" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-139">&#91;130&#93;</a></sup> The 2019 Revision of the UN estimates gives the "medium variant" population as; nearly 8.6&#160;billion in 2030, about 9.7&#160;billion in 2050 and about 10.9&#160;billion in 2100.<sup id="cite_ref-140" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-140">&#91;131&#93;</a></sup> In December 2019, the <a href="/wiki/German_Foundation_for_World_Population" title="German Foundation for World Population">German Foundation for World Population</a> projected that the global population will reach 8&#160;billion by 2023 as it increases by 156 every minute.<sup id="cite_ref-141" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-141">&#91;132&#93;</a></sup> In a modeled future projection by the <a href="/wiki/Institute_for_Health_Metrics_and_Evaluation" title="Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation">Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation</a> the global population was projected to peak in 2064 at 9.73&#160;billion people and decline to 8.79&#160;billion in 2100.<sup id="cite_ref-142" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-142">&#91;133&#93;</a></sup> Some analysts have questioned the sustainability of further world population growth, highlighting the <a href="/wiki/Human_impact_on_the_environment" title="Human impact on the environment">growing pressures on the environment</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-StokstadAAAS_143-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-StokstadAAAS-143">&#91;134&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-144" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-144">&#91;135&#93;</a></sup> global food supplies, and energy resources.<sup id="cite_ref-145" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-145">&#91;136&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-TIMEenvir_146-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-TIMEenvir-146">&#91;137&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Zehner_147-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Zehner-147">&#91;138&#93;</a></sup>
</p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Mathematical_approximations">Mathematical approximations</span></h2>
<p>In 1975, <a href="/wiki/Sebastian_von_Hoerner" title="Sebastian von Hoerner">Sebastian von Hoerner</a> proposed a formula for population growth which represented <a href="/wiki/Hyperbolic_growth" title="Hyperbolic growth">hyperbolic growth</a> with an infinite population in 2025.<sup id="cite_ref-150" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-150">&#91;141&#93;</a></sup> The hyperbolic growth of the world population observed until the 1970s was later correlated to a non-linear second-order positive feedback between demographic growth and technological development. This feedback can be described as follows: technological advance → increase in the <a href="/wiki/Carrying_capacity" title="Carrying capacity">carrying capacity</a> of land for people → demographic growth → more people → more potential inventors → acceleration of technological advance → accelerating growth of the carrying capacity → faster population growth → accelerating growth of the number of potential inventors → faster technological advance → hence, the faster growth of the Earth's carrying capacity for people, and so on.<sup id="cite_ref-151" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-151">&#91;142&#93;</a></sup> The transition from hyperbolic growth to slower rates of growth is related to the demographic transition.
</p><p>According to the Russian demographer <a href="/wiki/Sergey_Kapitsa" title="Sergey Kapitsa">Sergey Kapitsa</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-Kapitza_152-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kapitza-152">&#91;143&#93;</a></sup> the world population grew between 67,000&#160;BC and 1965 according to the following formula:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class="mwe-math-element"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext="{\displaystyle N={\frac {C}{\tau }}\operatorname {arccot} {\frac {T_{0}-T}{\tau }},}">
<semantics>
<mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
<mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">
<mi>N</mi>
<mo>=</mo>
<mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
<mfrac>
<mi>C</mi>
<mi>&#x03C4;<!-- τ --></mi>
</mfrac>
</mrow>
<mi>arccot</mi>
<mo>&#x2061;<!-- ⁡ --></mo>
<mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
<mfrac>
<mrow>
<msub>
<mi>T</mi>
<mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
<mn>0</mn>
</mrow>
</msub>
<mo>&#x2212;<!-- − --></mo>
<mi>T</mi>
</mrow>
<mi>&#x03C4;<!-- τ --></mi>
</mfrac>
</mrow>
<mo>,</mo>
</mstyle>
</mrow>
<annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle N={\frac {C}{\tau }}\operatorname {arccot} {\frac {T_{0}-T}{\tau }},}</annotation>
</semantics>
</math></span><img src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/5343454561d001d6d023b1aa36f88b54febb1349" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -1.838ex; width:23.116ex; height:5.343ex;" alt="{\displaystyle N={\frac {C}{\tau }}\operatorname {arccot} {\frac {T_{0}-T}{\tau }},}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>where
</p>

<dd><i>T</i><sub>0</sub> = 2007 ± 1,</dd>
<dd><span class="mwe-math-element"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext="{\displaystyle \tau }">

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Years_for_world_population_to_double">Years for world population to double</span></h3>
<p>According to linear interpolation and extrapolation of <a href="/wiki/Estimates_of_historical_world_population" title="Estimates of historical world population">UNDESA population estimates</a>, the world population has doubled, or will double, in the years listed in the tables below (with two different starting points). During the <a href="/wiki/2nd_millennium" title="2nd millennium">2nd millennium</a>, each doubling took roughly half as long as the previous doubling, fitting the hyperbolic growth model mentioned above. However, after 2024, it is unlikely that there will be another doubling of the global population in the 21st century.<sup id="cite_ref-153" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-153">&#91;144&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Population-doubling.svg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/18/Population-doubling.svg/300px-Population-doubling.svg.png" decoding="async" width="300" height="221" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/18/Population-doubling.svg/450px-Population-doubling.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/18/Population-doubling.svg/600px-Population-doubling.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="400" data-file-height="295" /></a><figcaption>Historic chart showing the periods of time the world population has taken to double, from 1700 to 2000</figcaption></figure>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Number_of_humans_who_have_ever_lived">Number of humans who have ever lived</span></h2>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Further information: <a href="/wiki/Prehistoric_demography" title="Prehistoric demography">Prehistoric demography</a></div>
<p>The total number of humans who have ever lived is estimated to be approximately <a href="/wiki/1E11" class="mw-redirect" title="1E11">100&#160;billion</a>. Such estimates can only be rough approximations, as even modern population estimates are subject to uncertainty of around 3% to 5%.<sup id="cite_ref-Kapitza2_14-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kapitza2-14">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup> Kapitsa (1996) cites estimates ranging between 80 and 150&#160;billion.<sup id="cite_ref-155" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-155">&#91;146&#93;</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Population_Reference_Bureau" title="Population Reference Bureau">PRB</a> puts the figure at 117&#160;billion as of 2020, estimating that the current world population is 6.7% of all the humans who have ever lived.<sup id="cite_ref-156" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-156">&#91;147&#93;</a></sup> Haub (1995) prepared another figure, updated in 2002 and 2011; the 2011 figure was approximately 107&#160;billion.<sup id="cite_ref-Curtin2007_157-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Curtin2007-157">&#91;148&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Haub1995_158-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Haub1995-158">&#91;149&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Haub2011_159-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Haub2011-159">&#91;150&#93;</a></sup> Haub characterized this figure as an estimate that required "selecting population sizes for different points from antiquity to the present and applying assumed birth rates to each period".<sup id="cite_ref-Haub1995_158-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Haub1995-158">&#91;149&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Robust population data only exist for the last two or three centuries. Until the late 18th century, few governments had ever performed an accurate census. In many early attempts, such as in <a href="/wiki/Census_in_Egypt" title="Census in Egypt">Ancient Egypt</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Achaemenid_Empire" title="Achaemenid Empire">Persian Empire</a>, the focus was on counting merely a subset of the population for purposes of taxation or military service.<sup id="cite_ref-160" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-160">&#91;151&#93;</a></sup> Thus, there is a significant margin of error when estimating ancient global populations.
</p><p>Pre-modern <a href="/wiki/Infant_mortality" title="Infant mortality">infant mortality</a> rates are another critical factor for such an estimate; these rates are very difficult to estimate for ancient times due to a lack of accurate records. Haub (1995) estimates that around 40% of those who have ever lived did not survive beyond their first birthday. Haub also stated that "<a href="/wiki/Life_expectancy_at_birth" class="mw-redirect" title="Life expectancy at birth">life expectancy at birth</a> probably averaged only about ten years for most of human history",<sup id="cite_ref-Haub1995_158-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Haub1995-158">&#91;149&#93;</a></sup> which is not to be mistaken for the life expectancy after reaching adulthood. The latter equally depended on period, location and social standing, but <a href="/wiki/Life_expectancy#Variation_over_time" title="Life expectancy">calculations</a> identify averages from roughly 30&#160;years upward.
</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/National_Institute_of_Corrections" title="National Institute of Corrections">National Institute of Corrections</a> estimates that that the number of people who have ever lived will rise to 121&#160;billion by 2050, 4&#160;billion more than their 2021 estimate.<sup id="cite_ref-161" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-161">&#91;152&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Human_population_as_a_function_of_food_availability">Human population as a function of food availability</span></h2>
<p>Individuals from a wide range of academic fields and political backgrounds have proposed that, like all other animal populations, any <a href="/wiki/Human_population" class="mw-redirect" title="Human population">human population</a> (and, by extension, the world population) predictably grows and shrinks according to available food supply, growing during an abundance of food and shrinking in times of scarcity.<sup id="cite_ref-162" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-162">&#91;153&#93;</a></sup> This idea may run counter to the popular thinking that, as population grows, food supply must also be increased to support the growing population; instead, the claim here is that growing population is the <i>result</i> of a growing food supply. Notable proponents of this notion include: <a href="/wiki/Agronomist" class="mw-redirect" title="Agronomist">agronomist</a> and insect ecologist <a href="/wiki/David_Pimentel_(scientist)" title="David Pimentel (scientist)">David Pimentel</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-Hopfenberg_and_Pimentel_163-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Hopfenberg_and_Pimentel-163">&#91;154&#93;</a></sup> behavioral scientist Russell Hopfenberg (the former two publishing a study on the topic in 2001),<sup id="cite_ref-164" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-164">&#91;155&#93;</a></sup> anthropologist and activist <a href="/wiki/Virginia_Abernethy" title="Virginia Abernethy">Virginia Abernethy</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-165" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-165">&#91;156&#93;</a></sup> ecologist <a href="/wiki/Garrett_Hardin" title="Garrett Hardin">Garrett Hardin</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-166" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-166">&#91;157&#93;</a></sup> science writer and anthropologist <a href="/wiki/Peter_Farb" title="Peter Farb">Peter Farb</a>, journalist <a href="/wiki/Richard_Manning" title="Richard Manning">Richard Manning</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-167" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-167">&#91;158&#93;</a></sup> environmental biologist Alan D. Thornhill,<sup id="cite_ref-168" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-168">&#91;159&#93;</a></sup> cultural critic and writer <a href="/wiki/Daniel_Quinn" title="Daniel Quinn">Daniel Quinn</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-169" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-169">&#91;160&#93;</a></sup> and <a href="/wiki/Anarcho-primitivist" class="mw-redirect" title="Anarcho-primitivist">anarcho-primitivist</a> <a href="/wiki/John_Zerzan" title="John Zerzan">John Zerzan</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-170" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-170">&#91;161&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Scientists generally acknowledge that at least one significant factor contributing to population growth (or overpopulation) is that as agriculture advances in creating more food, the population consequently increases&#8212;the <a href="/wiki/Neolithic_Revolution" title="Neolithic Revolution">Neolithic Revolution</a> and <a href="/wiki/Green_Revolution" title="Green Revolution">Green Revolution</a> often specifically provided as examples of such agricultural breakthroughs.<sup id="cite_ref-Gilland_171-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gilland-171">&#91;162&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-172" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-172">&#91;163&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Li_173-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Li-173">&#91;164&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-174" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-174">&#91;165&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-175" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-175">&#91;166&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-NatGeo_176-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NatGeo-176">&#91;167&#93;</a></sup> Furthermore, certain scientific studies do lend evidence to food availability in particular being the dominant factor within a more recent timeframe.<sup id="cite_ref-177" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-177">&#91;168&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-178" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-178">&#91;169&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Hopfenberg_and_Pimentel_163-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Hopfenberg_and_Pimentel-163">&#91;154&#93;</a></sup> Other studies take it as a basic model from which to make broad population conjectures.<sup id="cite_ref-Gilland_171-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gilland-171">&#91;162&#93;</a></sup> The idea became <a href="/wiki/Taboo" title="Taboo">taboo</a> following the United Nations' 1994 <a href="/wiki/International_Conference_on_Population_and_Development" title="International Conference on Population and Development">International Conference on Population and Development</a>, where framing human population growth as negatively impacting the natural environment became regarded as "anti-human".<sup id="cite_ref-179" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-179">&#91;170&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Most human populations throughout history validate this theory, as does the overall current global population. Populations of <a href="/wiki/Hunter-gatherer" title="Hunter-gatherer">hunter-gatherers</a> fluctuate in accordance with the amount of available food. The world human population began consistently and sharply to rise, and continues to do so, after sedentary agricultural lifestyles became common due to the Neolithic Revolution and its increased food supply.<sup id="cite_ref-180" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-180">&#91;171&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Li_173-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Li-173">&#91;164&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-NatGeo_176-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NatGeo-176">&#91;167&#93;</a></sup> This was, subsequent to the Green Revolution starting in the 1940s, followed by even more severely accelerated population growth. Often, wealthier countries send their surplus food resources to the aid of starving communities; however, some proponents of this theory argue that this seemingly beneficial strategy only results in further harm to those communities in the long run. Anthropologist Peter Farb, for example, has commented on the paradox that "intensification of production to feed an increased population leads to a still greater increase in population."<sup id="cite_ref-181" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-181">&#91;172&#93;</a></sup> Environmental writer Daniel Quinn has also focused on this phenomenon, which he calls the "food race", coining a term he felt was comparable, in terms of both escalation and potential catastrophe, to the <a href="/wiki/Nuclear_arms_race" title="Nuclear arms race">nuclear arms race</a>.
</p><p>Criticism of this theory can come from multiple angles, for example by demonstrating that human population is not solely an effect of food availability, but that the situation is more complex. For instance, other relevant factors that can increase or limit human population include fresh water availability, arable land availability, energy consumed per person, heat removal, forest products, and various nonrenewable resources like fertilizers.<sup id="cite_ref-182" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-182">&#91;173&#93;</a></sup> Another criticism is that, in the modern era, birth rates are lowest in the <a href="/wiki/Developed_nation" class="mw-redirect" title="Developed nation">developed nations</a>, which also have the highest access to food. In fact, some developed countries have both a diminishing population and an abundant food supply. The United Nations projects that the population of 51 countries or areas, including Germany, Italy, Japan, and most of the states of the former Soviet Union, is expected to be lower in 2050 than in 2005.<sup id="cite_ref-183" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-183">&#91;174&#93;</a></sup> This shows that, limited to the scope of the population living within a single given political boundary, particular human populations do not always grow to match the available food supply. However, the global population as a whole still grows in accordance with the total food supply and many of these wealthier countries are major <i>exporters</i> of food to poorer populations, so that, according to Hopfenberg and Pimentel's 2001 research, "it is through exports from food-rich to food-poor areas... that the population growth in these food-poor areas is further fueled.<sup id="cite_ref-Hopfenberg_and_Pimentel_163-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Hopfenberg_and_Pimentel-163">&#91;154&#93;</a></sup> Their study thus suggests that human population growth is an <a href="/wiki/Positive_feedback" title="Positive feedback">exacerbating feedback loop</a> in which food availability creates a growing population, which then causes the misimpression that food production must be consequently expanded even further.<sup id="cite_ref-184" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-184">&#91;175&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Regardless of criticisms against the theory that population is a function of food availability, the human population is, on the global scale, undeniably increasing,<sup id="cite_ref-185" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-185">&#91;176&#93;</a></sup> as is the net quantity of human food produced—a pattern that has been true for roughly 10,000 years, since the human development of agriculture. The fact that some affluent countries demonstrate negative population growth fails to discredit the theory as a whole, since the world has become a <a href="/wiki/Globalization" title="Globalization">globalized system</a> with food moving across national borders from areas of abundance to areas of scarcity. Hopfenberg and Pimentel's 2001 findings support both this<sup id="cite_ref-Hopfenberg_and_Pimentel_163-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Hopfenberg_and_Pimentel-163">&#91;154&#93;</a></sup> and Daniel Quinn's direct accusation, in the early 2010s, that "First World farmers are fueling the Third World population explosion".<sup id="cite_ref-186" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-186">&#91;177&#93;</a></sup>
</p>

<li id="cite_note-11"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-11">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">the <a href="/wiki/English_compound" title="English compound">compound</a> "world population" becomes common from c. the 1930s, adapted from early 20th-century "world's population"; pre-20th century authors use "population of the world".</span>

<li id="cite_note-12"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-12">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">"The population of the world, which Sir W. P. in 1682, stated at only 320 millions, has been estimated by some writers at about 730&#160;million, by others, at upwards of 900&#160;million; Mr. Wallace, of Edinburgh, conjectured it might amount to 1&#160;billion, and this number has since generally been adopted who have noticed the subject;" <i>The Monthly Magazine</i> 4 (July–December 1797), <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=0S0AAAAAYAAJ&amp;pg=PA167">p. 167</a>.</span>

<li id="cite_note-13"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-13">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">600&#160;million: Simon Gray, <i>The Happiness of States</i> (1818), <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=ue5eAAAAcAAJ&amp;pg=PA356">p. 356</a> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20190606203312/https://books.google.com/books?id=ue5eAAAAcAAJ&amp;pg=PA356">Archived</a> 6 June 2019 at the <a href="/wiki/Wayback_Machine" title="Wayback Machine">Wayback Machine</a>.

<li id="cite_note-Kapitza2-14"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Kapitza2_14-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Kapitza2_14-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">"[E]ven recent demographic data is accurate only from 3 to 5%, although in demography traditionally more digits are indicated than those having a meaning. This is partially due to the ethical difficulty in rounding off numbers that supposedly represent real people, officially counted during a census". Sergei P.&#160;Kapitza, "The phenomenological theory of world population growth", <i>Physics-Uspekhi</i> 39(1) 57–71 (1996).</span>
